(Deutsche Welle Chinese) The Biden administration this Friday (Feb. 10) blacklisted six Chinese entities associated with a suspected spy balloon program.
The U.S. Department of Commerce said the five Chinese companies and a research institute help modernize China's military, particularly its aerospace programs, including blimps and aircraft.
Blacklisted companies have difficulty obtaining U.S. technology exports.
The list is known as the "entity list," and companies on it are unable to purchase technology or goods from U.S. suppliers unless they receive a special export license from the U.S. Department of Commerce.
The blacklisted companies are: Beijing Nanjiang Air & Space Technology Co., Ltd, China Electronics Technology Group Forty-eighth Research Institute, Dongguan Lingkong Remote Sensing Technology Co., Ltd, Eagle Gate Aeronautical Science & Technology Group Co., Ltd, Guangzhou Tianhaixiang Aeronautical Science & Technology Co., Ltd and Shanxi Eagle Gate Aeronautical Science & Technology Group Co.
This comes after the White House said it was considering broader measures to "expose and address" China's larger surveillance activities that threaten U.S. national security.
The balloon incident triggered further tensions between the U.S. and China, and U.S. Secretary of State Abraham Blinken canceled his visit to China.
In response to the shooting down of the balloon by the United States on 4 February, the Chinese Government lodged solemn representations with the United States Embassy in Beijing, criticizing the United States for seriously impacting on and undermining the efforts and processes of both sides to stabilize China-United States relations.
From the available evidence of wreckage and information on the Chinese military's procurement platform, the United States Government concluded that the balloon's manufacturer had a "direct relationship with the Chinese People's Liberation Army" and was an approved supplier to the Chinese military.
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Mao Ning said at a news conference on Friday that China has repeatedly explained the situation and clarified its position on the accidental incident of a Chinese unmanned civilian blimp that mistakenly entered U.S. airspace due to force majeure.
According to the Foreign Ministry's website, she added that the relevant resolution in the U.S. Congress was pure political maneuvering and speculation.
China is strongly dissatisfied with and firmly opposes this.
Matthew Axelrod, Assistant Secretary for Export Enforcement at the U.S. Department of Commerce, said: "Today's action demonstrates a concerted effort to identify and stop China's use of spy balloons, which violate the airspace of the U.S. and more than 40 countries.
"
Reuters reported that an employee of Guangzhou Tianhaixiang Aeronautical Science and Technology Co. said she was unaware of the sanctions and declined to comment further.
The Chinese Embassy in the U.S. and has not yet commented on this information.
