(Deutsche Welle) Days after the earthquake hit parts of Turkey and Syria, hopes of finding survivors are fading, but searchers were overwhelmed by the rescue of a family of five on Saturday.
The family of five was successfully rescued after being trapped under the rubble for more than five days in the hard-hit town of Nourdai in Gaziantep province, the Associated Press reported.
Searchers first pulled the mother and daughter from a pile of rubble and then found the father, but he insisted that his son and another daughter be saved first.
When they were all rescued, the crowd erupted in cheers.
In the southern Turkish city of Kahramanmaraş, a 16-year-old boy and a 70-year-old woman were also successfully rescued in harsh and bitterly cold weather conditions.
"What day is it now?
"- The teenager who was trapped under the rubble for 129 hours asked the searchers who rescued him after he was brought back to the surface.
A Kahramanmarash man holds his newly rescued cat
Miraculously successful rescue cases have brought a ray of hope to an already hopeless search and rescue effort, but at the same time, the number of victims continues to rise.
Monday's quake has now killed more than 20,000 people in Turkey, according to official statistics, with the death toll in neighboring Syria estimated at more than 3,500 people.
Although experts say people can survive for up to a week or more after being trapped in the rubble, hopes of finding more survivors have become increasingly remote.
Rescuers are still probing for signs of life beneath the rubble with the help of thermal imaging cameras.
At the same time, the focus of rescue efforts began to shift to helping survivors who were in dire need of help.
U.N. official: Disaster 'not seen in a century' in region
Martin Griffiths, the UN Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs and Emergency Relief Coordinator, told a press conference in Turkey that the quake was the region's "worst catastrophe in a century".
He also praised Turkey's post-disaster response as "extraordinary".
He also told Reuters that he hoped relief would be delivered to areas controlled by both the Syrian government and the opposition, but also said the matter was "unclear".
The United Nations has pledged an additional $25 million in relief contributions to the earthquake-affected population in Syria.
Earlier this week, the United Nations had announced $25 million for disaster relief in Turkey and Syria.
The most destructive earthquake to hit the world in 60 years
Great Chilean Earthquake (1960)
On May 22, 1960, at 3:11 p.m. local time, the largest earthquake ever observed and recorded in human history occurred in Valdivia, Chile, with a seismic moment magnitude of 9.5
In just ten minutes, the entire city of Valdivia was reduced to rubble.
A huge tsunami triggered by the earthquake hit the Chilean coastline, creating a massive wave height of 25 meters.
The tsunami reached as far away as Japan and the Philippines.
The number of victims and the economic damage caused by a disaster of this magnitude cannot be known with precision.
The most destructive earthquake to hit the world in 60 years
Great Alaskan Earthquake (1964)
March 27, 1964 was a Friday and was also Good Friday.
On this day the largest earthquake in the history of North America occurred in Alaska, USA, with a moment magnitude of 9.2.
Until 2006, the Great Alaska Earthquake remained the third largest earthquake in the world on record.
The earthquake occurred when a fault between the Pacific and North American plates broke in Prince William Sound near College Gap.
The quake lasted between three and five minutes in most areas.
Displacement of the seabed triggered a huge tsunami with a height of 67 meters.
Since it was a holiday, schools and many businesses were closed.
The earthquake ended up killing 139 people.
Nine of them died as a direct result of the earthquake, while 130 others died as a result of the tsunami triggered by the earthquake.
The most destructive earthquake to hit the world in 60 years
Tangshan Earthquake (1976)
On July 28, 1976, two powerful earthquakes of magnitude 7 or higher occurred within 16 hours in Tangshan City and Fengnan County, Hebei Province, China.
The epicenter was 23 kilometers above the ground.
Transportation, communication, water supply and power supply were interrupted in the city of Tangshan, which was razed to the ground in an instant.
Strong tremors were also felt 140 kilometers away in the capital, Beijing.
According to official statistics, the earthquake killed 242,769 people and seriously injured 164,851 in all affected areas, including Beijing and Tianjin.
The Tangshan earthquake became the second deadliest earthquake on record in China to date, after the 1556 Jiajing earthquake.
But some overseas scientists estimate that the quake could have killed at least 650,000 people.
The most destructive earthquake to hit the world in 60 years
Indian Ocean earthquake (2004)
On December 26, 2004, an earthquake struck 160 kilometers off the west coast of Aceh province on the island of Sumatra, Indonesia, at a depth of 30 kilometers, with a moment magnitude of 9.1 to 9.3.
The earthquake triggered a huge tsunami with wave heights of 15 to 30 meters.
A total of 14 countries along the Pacific coast were affected, with the worst hit areas including Aceh province in Indonesia, the resort areas of Ho Chi Minh and Phuket in Thailand, Sri Lanka and the Indian state of Tamil.
It was during the peak tourist season of Christmas, and the affected area was crowded with travelers and local residents, causing many travelers enjoying their vacation on the beach and locals working on the beach to be swept under the sea by the tsunami, making many people missing from this earthquake.
The number of dead and missing is estimated to be at least 300,000 people.
The most destructive earthquake to hit the world in 60 years
Wenchuan Earthquake (2008)
On May 12, 2008, a massive earthquake struck the Wenchuan region of China's Sichuan Province.
According to the China Earthquake Administration, the quake had a magnitude of 8.2 on the surface wave scale and 8.3 on the moment scale, damaging an area of more than 100,000 square kilometers.
As of September 25, 2008, a total of 69,227 people had been killed, 17,923 were missing, 374,643 were injured to varying degrees, 199,300 people had lost their homes, and the total number of people affected by the earthquake was 46,256,000 people.
It was the most destructive earthquake since the founding of the People's Republic of China and the deadliest since the Tangshan earthquake.
In March 2009, China's State Council announced that May 12 of each year would be designated as Disaster Prevention and Mitigation Day, to strengthen education for the public and focus on disaster prevention and mitigation efforts.
Since then, many governments and primary and secondary schools in China have held earthquake drills on this day every year.
Primary and secondary schools have also begun to emphasize the popularization of "earthquake prevention and mitigation" education.
The most destructive earthquake to hit the world in 60 years
Haiti earthquake (2010)
On January 12, 2010, an earthquake measuring 7.0 on the Richter scale struck the Caribbean island nation of Haiti.
The epicenter of the earthquake was located 25 kilometers south-southwest of Port-au-Prince, the capital of Haiti, and the epicenter was about 13 kilometers from the surface.
The International Red Cross estimates that the population affected by the earthquake is approximately 3 million.
The Haitian government has announced a confirmed death toll of more than 200,000 people.
In some areas within Haiti, as many as 90 percent of the homes were destroyed in the earthquake.
Despite massive assistance and support from the international community, the impoverished country, overpopulated and riddled with corruption, never recovered from the disaster.
The most destructive earthquake to hit the world in 60 years
Tohoku Earthquake in Japan (2011)
On March 11, 2011, a large inversion zone earthquake with a moment magnitude of 9.0 occurred off the Tohoku region of Japan.
The epicenter of the earthquake was located in the Pacific Ocean east of Sendai, the capital of Miyagi Prefecture, and the depth of the quake was measured at 24 kilometers, triggering a huge tsunami with a maximum height of 40.1 meters.
The quake was the first earthquake with a magnitude of more than 9 in Japan's recorded history.
About 22,000 people lost their lives in the disaster and about 400,000 buildings were completely destroyed or collapsed.
The Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant suffered a leak due to the earthquake and tsunami.
The accident was categorized as the most serious level 7 on the International Nuclear Event Scale (INES).
As a result of the Fukushima nuclear accident, trace amounts of radioactive substances, including iodine-131 and cesium-137 (with a half-life of 30 years), have been measured all over the world.
A large number of radioisotopes were released into the Pacific Ocean as a result of the nuclear accident.
According to the United Nations, at least 870,000 people are currently in urgent need of food in the affected areas of Turkey and Syria.
In Syria alone, as many as 5.3 million people have lost their homes to earthquakes.
The World Food Program (WFP) has appealed for $77 million to feed victims displaced by the earthquake in Turkey and Syria.
Temperatures in the affected areas are currently below zero, and many victims are without shelter.
The Turkish government has distributed large quantities of hot meals, tents and blankets, but these supplies are still struggling to reach many people in desperate need.
In Syria, which has been mired in civil war for 12 years, the earthquake added to the suffering of the population.
In the four days since the earthquake, the World Food Program has provided food relief to 115,000 people in Turkey and Syria.
For its part, the World Health Organization (WHO) sent 72 tons of medical supplies for trauma care and emergency surgery.
