NEWS GOV-MO: Police Notice: SZPD urges citizens to beware of fraudulent SMS from fake telecommunication companies
Recently, the SFPD has received a number of cases of telecommunication fraud in which criminals, posing as local telecommunication companies, send fraudulent SMS with links to websites to lure customers to log in to fraudulent websites for redemption under the bait that they must redeem their bonus points as soon as possible after their points expire.
The victim entered his credit card information and verification code as instructed, and then received a notification from the financial institution that there were unidentified purchase records on his credit card and that he suspected that his credit card information had been stolen through the above website.
Upon checking, it was confirmed that the relevant telecommunications company had not sent the said SMS.
The SFPD urges members of the public to be vigilant if they receive similar SMS messages on their cell phones, and not to log in to the website link contained in the message or provide any personal information; if they are asked to provide credit card information, account transaction passwords, transaction verification codes, they should be doubly cautious in order to prevent credit card theft.
Fraud Prevention Tip:
1. Pay more attention to information on network security and raise your awareness of personal precautions;
2. Do not log on to websites of unknown origin and register your personal and credit card information on such websites to prevent unauthorized use;
3. Be wary of fake and phishing websites, and always look out for website URLs that match the official website exactly;
4. Install anti-virus software for your cell phone, mobile device or computer and update it regularly;
5. If you suspect that you have encountered fraud or other crimes, you should immediately call the fraud prevention inquiry hotline of the Police Department at 8800 7777 or the crime reporting hotline at 993 for assistance.
