French trade unions mobilize again in march against government's retirement reform proposal
On Saturday (February 11), French trade unions again launched a national mobilization against the government's draft pension reform, calling on people to take to the streets to express their opinions.
This is the fourth day of action of this social wave against the government's draft pension system reform.
And how many people respond to the rally call could affect the union group's next course of action.
This is the fourth time in a month that France's eight largest trade union groups have come together to launch a national mobilization, and the first time this protest has scheduled a rally for a Saturday.
Given that for most French people Saturday is a public holiday, they don't have to choose between taking part in demonstrations and protests or going on strike with wage deductions, union groups are therefore hoping that today's rallies will attract more people.
Neither the unions of the bus system Metro nor the public railroads called for a strike of their employees today, and the bus system should be able to function normally, with people able to ride to rallies, while people can depart for their vacations as normal in areas where schools have begun their winter breaks.
Trade union groups are hoping for more than a million people to attend the rally today, while police are expecting a possible national turnout of between 600,000 and 800,000, with between 90,000 and 120,000 people likely to gather in the Paris metropolitan area.
Since the beginning of this protest against the government's pension reform program, the number of people actually taking to the streets to participate in the march has gradually decreased, although polls show that most French people do not support the measure to postpone the mandatory retirement age from the current 62 to 64.
The first strike demonstrations on January 31st rallied between 1.27 and 2.5 million people across the country.
And the crowds at this Tuesday's (Feb. 7) demonstration have shrunk to between 757,000 and two million nationwide.
This pension reform proposal is currently being discussed in the French National Assembly.
The opposition parties, especially those led by the radical left, have submitted numerous amendment proposals, so that the review process is moving forward very slowly.
And the debate between the court and the opposition is getting more and more heated and sharp.
A lawmaker from the radical left-wing party France Indomitable recently triggered a protest from the ruling party by transmitting on social media an image of himself with his foot in a balloon bearing the head of the labor minister.
The Speaker of the National Assembly eventually announced a 15-day ban on the member's participation in parliamentary activities as a punishment for such behavior.
Despite the fact that this reform program has triggered the largest social upheaval in France in the last 20 years or so, the government has so far not made any major concessions, although it has tweaked the draft slightly.
The unions are already preparing to launch another action next Thursday, the 16th, and they are also planning to organize demonstrations on March 7th, when the draft reform is sent to the Senate for discussion.
