East Germany's last communist chancellor died today
The successor of the Communist Party of East Germany reported in a statement from the party, "Last night, Hans Modrow left us at the age of 95.
As a result, our party has lost an important leader.
"
On November 13, 1989, four days after the opening of the Berlin Wall that had separated East and West Berlin for 28 years, Modrow had said he would help turn East Germany into a democracy.
At that time, communist leaders were forced to step down as protesters across East Germany demanded democracy and freedom.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in the Soviet Union, he called for change in Soviet-dominated Eastern Europe as well.
In March 1990, Modrow announced the first and only free elections in the German Democratic Republic (GDR).
The results of the election resulted in his ceasing to be Prime Minister.
Despite Modrow's reforms, opponents accused him of trying to delay the political change and unification that occurred in October 1990.3 The government's efforts to reform the country's political system have been a major challenge to the country's economy.
He has also been criticized for trying to reinvent rather than abolish the secret police.
In 1993, Modrow was convicted of electoral fraud in the May 1989 municipal elections, but did not go to prison.
It has been claimed that these allegations are politically motivated.
Modrow continued to serve in the German Parliament from 1990 to 1994 and was a Member of the European Parliament from 1999 to 2004.
Modrow saw himself as a reformer and wanted to change the Communist Party from within.
In 1999, he told Reuters that he did not want the old GDR to return, but said that the GDR's achievements should be recognized.
Modrow was born in 1928 in the then German town of Jasenitz (now Jasienica, Poland) and trained as a machinist.
During World War II, he served as a platoon leader in a youth fire department and near the end of the conflict became a member of the Nazi militia, the Volkssturm, which recruited men between the ages of 16 and 60 to fight in the final struggles of the war.
At the age of 17, Modrow was captured by Soviet forces and taken as a prisoner of war to the Soviet Union, where he took anti-fascist courses and became a staunch communist.
In 1949, the year of the founding of East Germany, he returned to his home country and found work as a machinist and continued his studies in social sciences and economics, earning a Ph.
Modrow was a staff member of the Free German Youth Movement, to which almost all young people in East Germany belonged, and rose through the ruling Social Unity Party (SED) to become chairman of the regional party in Dresden between 1973 and 1989.
He also served in the East German Parliament for more than 30 years.
In 1990, Modrow became the de facto leader of East Germany, holding the highest state office.
