What exactly was the "object" shot down over Alaska?
Confusion and speculation abound
The U.S. military once again used the F-22, America's most advanced stealth jet fighter, to shoot down an as-yet-unidentified object flying over the U.S. state of Alaska on Friday (Feb. 10) afternoon.
The location of the shoot down was ten miles off the coast of Alaska.
This is the second time in less than a week that the U.S. military has shot down an airborne object.
On Saturday, a spy balloon from China was destroyed over the U.S. coast near South Carolina after drifting through U.S. airspace for several days.
The Pentagon said the second downed object, which first entered U.S. airspace on Thursday night, was tracked by the U.S. military as it moved over northeastern Alaska, flying at an altitude of 12,000 meters (40,000 feet) and was about the size of a small car, much smaller than the Chinese spy balloon that was shot down earlier.
The Pentagon also believes that there is no indication that the object is manipulable.
John Kirby, coordinator of strategic communications for the White House's National Security Council, said Friday that while the exact appearance of the object flying at high altitude was unclear, it "poses a legitimate threat to the safety of civil aircraft."
Kirby said the object was different from the spy balloon found in the U.S. in that it did not have a "payload" hanging from it.
"We call it an 'object' is the best description we can make at this point", Kirby said.
President Biden took advice from the Pentagon before ordering the object shot down, and he made that decision "very carefully," Kirby added.
The official U.S. description of the object can be roughly summarized as being the size of a small car, with no joystick, no suspension, and flying at an altitude of about 10,000 meters.
But this information does not yet answer basic questions, such as what exactly this object is, which country it belongs to, and what mission it is on.
Much of the current analysis and speculation online suggests that this could be another Chinese balloon.
It may have come from China as did the spy balloon that invaded U.S. airspace and the Chinese balloon that floated over Latin America on some kind of mission in a different location.
Others have linked the Alaska "object" to "unidentified flying objects" (UFOs).
The Newsweek story quotes former U.S. Rep. Peter Meijer (R-N.Y.) as tweeting Friday, "I really hope this 'UFO' is also a spy balloon and not a legitimate UFO" .
"The irony of conflating an alien spacecraft with a weather balloon is surprising, but it's not worth starting an interstellar conflict," Major said.
Major sent this tweet shortly after Kirby confirmed that this object in Alaska had been shot down.
Newsweek said Major was not the only one who suspected the object was a UFO.
Tennessee Republican Rep. Tim Burchett (R-Tennessee) criticized the administration's cover-up last month, calling on the Office of the Director of National Intelligence (DNI) to release its report on the "unidentified flying object".
