Not really recommended reading
I read it a long time ago, and I happened to see it and write something about it from memory.
This book is not so much a collection of short stories as it is a collection of pieces of life about love.
The tone of the book is extremely plain, the kind of plain as plain as plain water, the wordplay goes to the extreme of simplicity, and the plot is as silent and bland as a street on a summer afternoon.
Each short story is a snapshot of a small period of time in ordinary life, with no beginning and no end.
Finally collected together under the title What We Talk About When We Talk About Love.
I think this collection of stories, and its title, is like a kind of performance art, the author wants to express that love is more than just the sadness and joy on the stage, the urban legend of the sea and the rocks, and not just you and me like glue, love is more than the above nor should it be represented by the above, love is also a life as plain as water, boring day by day, there is also the life of the unpreparedness, the reality of the escape, the future of the The future is uncertain.
As you read this book your mind may go back to the bickering couple next to you, the tasteless marriages of people you know, and less-than-ideal relationships.
This is exactly why I don't recommend reading it; aesthetically, the writing and plot of this book are tasteless, and unless your life is amazing or sweet as living in a candy castle, you'll have to read it with the feeling that you've seen it all and are bored.
And in terms of depth of thought, the everyday episodes don't brighten or expand one's thoughts or horizons (unlike Marquez's Love in the Time of Cholera in this regard), nor do the brief segments explore any questions, such as what kind of mistakes lead to the failure of love?
The breakdown of the protagonist's marriage stems from those reasons?
So I don't recommend reading this book, it doesn't make much sense to read it or not.
The author's ideas are expressed more through technique and genre than storyline, and is the reason why this book is a poorer reading experience.
